T1  - Domestic constraints on export-led growth: a case-study of India
AU  - Storm, Servaas
JO  - Journal of Development Economics
VL  - 52
IS  - 1
SP  - 83
EP  - 119
PY  - 1997
DA  - 1997/02/01/
SN  - 0304-3878
DO  - https://doi.org/10.1016/S0304-3878(96)00438-5
UR  - https://www.sciencedirect.com/science/article/pii/S0304387896004385
KW  - Indian development strategy
KW  - Agricultural policy
KW  - Trade policy
AB  - In light of the 1991–1993 Indian policy reforms, this paper assesses the feasibility of a strategy of manufacturing export-led growth for India. By means of simulation experiments using a nine-sector, seven-income classes computable general equilibrium model, developed for India's Seventh Plan period (1985–1990), the relative merits of this strategy are compared to those of an alternative open-development strategy (agricultural-demand-led industrialization) under both a fixed and flexible exchange rate regime. Compared to earlier models, the analysis adds disaggregated agricultural supply and income distribution, and export demand response. The results suggest that industrial growth can be self-defeating by raising the relative price of domestic goods and thereby running into an export-demand bottleneck. Hence, if a step-up in manufacturing exports is to contribute to a non-inflationary acceleration of GDP growth, it needs to be supplemented by adequate policies aimed at raising agricultural output and income.
